WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.812 --> 00:00:05.783
So good to see you.

00:00:05.783 --> 00:00:08.285
Welcome to Venice,
California. Thank you. Great

00:00:08.285 --> 00:00:09.285
to see you.

00:00:09.285 --> 00:00:10.170
I mean, you brought the sunshine,

00:00:10.170 --> 00:00:11.460
I think you brought the sunshine.

00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:13.680
It's nice. It's so beautiful.
Beautiful day out here.

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:18.680
I'm in sunny LA surrounded
by sand surf and skateboarders.

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.780
It may be far from the mega
campuses of Silicon Valley,

00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:23.820
but it's where Evan
Spiegel, the co-founder

00:00:23.820 --> 00:00:26.640
and CEO of Snap feels most at home.

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:29.520
10 million people walk the
boardwalk every single year.

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:32.250
And I think for us, that was so special

00:00:32.250 --> 00:00:34.740
because all these people
from all over the world were

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:36.150
walking by our office every single day.

00:00:36.150 --> 00:00:37.800
We had a big ghost logo out front.

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:41.040
Yep. You may know Snap, as
the popular messaging app made

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:43.380
for sending disappearing
photos and videos.

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:45.510
Some people can't handle success.

00:00:45.510 --> 00:00:46.560
I can

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:49.710
That had a meteoric rise
with Spiegel at its helm.

00:00:49.710 --> 00:00:52.050
Snapchat always starts with a snap

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:54.760
These days,

00:00:54.760 --> 00:00:57.150
he's grown up, still in founder mode

00:00:57.150 --> 00:00:59.850
and trying to stay competitive
in the ever-changing world

00:00:59.850 --> 00:01:02.070
of social media. To do that,

00:01:02.070 --> 00:01:05.130
Spiegel's doubling down
on consumer hardware

00:01:05.130 --> 00:01:08.280
and going head to head with
giants like Google, Meta

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:09.630
and Apple in the race

00:01:09.630 --> 00:01:12.150
to bring augmented reality to the masses.

00:01:12.150 --> 00:01:14.670
I think for us it's, it's
really about this transition

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:17.580
from a screen-based way of
interacting with computers,

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:19.680
to interacting with
computers in the real world

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:20.790
through augmented reality.

00:01:20.790 --> 00:01:22.740
That this is gonna be one of the biggest

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:25.350
and most profound shifts in, in computing.

00:01:25.350 --> 00:01:26.670
These are trillion
dollar companies though.

00:01:26.670 --> 00:01:28.890
And Snap is a multi-billion
dollar company.

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:30.450
A baby, a baby company.

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:32.880
A baby company. So he's on a quest

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:34.740
and having some fun along the way.

00:01:34.740 --> 00:01:36.390
I don't know where these
arrows are going, but,

00:01:37.265 --> 00:01:38.400
Oh,
Oh, there we go.

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:39.570
So we're looking at the future,

00:01:39.570 --> 00:01:41.940
literally right now. Is
that what we're doing?

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:42.773
Feels like it.

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:53.220
You grew up in Southern California.

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:54.420
What kind of kid were you?

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:55.860
Were you one of the cool kids

00:01:55.860 --> 00:01:58.020
or were you one of the
nerds trying to be cool?

00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:01.200
You know, I think my
wife always says it's cool

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.470
to be uncool, so I
definitely was not, not one

00:02:04.470 --> 00:02:06.120
of the cool kids.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:07.980
You know, I, I grew up in,
my parents didn't let me

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:09.360
watch TV at all.

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:11.400
Oh, really?
So I was very into reading.

00:02:11.400 --> 00:02:13.740
It's okay to be a nerd.
I was totally a nerd.

00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:15.330
I think we turned out okay.

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:17.070
I saw that you were really
interested in graphic

00:02:17.070 --> 00:02:19.260
design early on.

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:21.690
How did that sort of shape your approach?

00:02:21.690 --> 00:02:23.670
I think for me it was that
intersection of being able

00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:25.500
to express myself through art,

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:27.240
but to do it with the computer

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.940
and to use these really,
really powerful tools

00:02:29.940 --> 00:02:31.530
that made me feel like, you know,

00:02:31.530 --> 00:02:33.240
anything was, was possible.

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:35.220
And then later on that sort of prompted me

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:36.900
to build my own computer

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:40.170
and to pursue ultimately
product design in, in college.

00:02:40.170 --> 00:02:42.000
What was it that made you
say, I need to drop out?

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.860
Like I need to do this?

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:46.530
I I was standing in the
back of this machining class

00:02:46.530 --> 00:02:49.080
and I, at that time, we, we
were signed the documents.

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:51.510
We were waiting for our
venture investors Lightspeed

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:54.570
to fund, and I was refreshing
the Wells Fargo app in the

00:02:54.570 --> 00:02:57.660
back of the class, saw the
$485,000 hit, walked up

00:02:57.660 --> 00:02:59.170
to my teacher Craig,

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:00.670
and just said, you know
what, I'm so sorry,

00:03:00.670 --> 00:03:01.900
I'm gonna have to drop this class.

00:03:01.900 --> 00:03:03.190
But I went back

00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:06.430
and finished that class
with Craig many years later

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:08.710
When Snapchat debuted in 2011,

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.680
social media looked a little different.

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:13.240
MySpace was on its way out.

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:15.010
Facebook and Twitter were huge,

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:17.230
and Instagram had just launched.

00:03:17.230 --> 00:03:19.270
The startup economy was booming.

00:03:19.270 --> 00:03:20.270
At the time,

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:21.850
it would take like a minute to send a

00:03:21.850 --> 00:03:23.020
photo, which was just crazy.

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:24.370
So we invented a way to send

00:03:24.370 --> 00:03:26.020
photos really, really quickly.

00:03:26.020 --> 00:03:27.280
People were starting to use it to talk.

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:28.420
So we renamed it Snapchat,

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:29.800
we added captions and drawing

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:32.170
and all the fun creative tools people use.

00:03:32.170 --> 00:03:35.560
Within a few years, Snapchat
was rising in popularity.

00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:37.630
That is rainbow vomit

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:39.790
Stirring up its share of controversy

00:03:39.790 --> 00:03:41.830
and catching the attention
of Silicon Valley.

00:03:41.830 --> 00:03:44.590
I remember the first time
I saw Snapchat in the wild.

00:03:44.590 --> 00:03:45.850
We were at an ice cream parlor

00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:47.770
and there was this crowd
of kids in front of us

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:48.940
and they all had their phones up.

00:03:48.940 --> 00:03:49.870
And I was like, oh, they're taking

00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:51.190
pictures of the ice cream.

00:03:51.190 --> 00:03:53.445
And my husband whispered,
there's Snapchatting.

00:03:53.445 --> 00:03:56.920
And I was like, oh, this is,
this is becoming a thing.

00:03:56.920 --> 00:03:59.320
Like it was really a
moment. Teens everywhere

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:01.690
believe they're sending
their own self-destructing

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:03.820
messages online with an app called

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:04.840
Snapchat.

00:04:04.840 --> 00:04:06.280
Was there a sort of an inflection point

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:08.590
where you felt like
things really took off?

00:04:08.590 --> 00:04:10.600
Snapchat changed people's
relationship with photos

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:12.040
and made them about communicating.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:13.870
And it turns out people communicate way

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:15.100
more than they say things.

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:17.320
And so there was a moment
in time when, you know,

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:20.650
we realized that the number
of photos people were taking

00:04:20.650 --> 00:04:22.360
and sending on Snapchat at, you know,

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:23.950
eclipsed the total number

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:26.950
of normal photos people were
taking on the world, you know,

00:04:26.950 --> 00:04:28.720
out in the world with their,
with their smartphones.

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:30.040
And I think that was really the moment

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:31.960
that we realized there
had been this huge shift

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:33.820
that like the majority use case

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:37.420
or the primary use case for
cameras was communicating,

00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:38.560
not saving things.

00:04:39.430 --> 00:04:41.680
The rise of Snapchat
also made Spiegel one

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:45.640
of the youngest billionaires
in the world by age 25.

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:49.540
How did you manage having so
much responsibility and money

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:51.430
and fame at such a young age?

00:04:51.430 --> 00:04:53.050
What a great question.

00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:54.790
I, you know, I, I felt really fortunate

00:04:54.790 --> 00:04:56.620
that I live in a place where my family is.

00:04:56.620 --> 00:04:59.830
So my family, my high school
buddies, my, like, all my,

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:01.150
you know, friends from, from school

00:05:01.150 --> 00:05:03.730
and from growing up are, are
here in la My parents live,

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:05.710
fortunately they're still
alive and live 10 minutes away.

00:05:05.710 --> 00:05:08.170
So I've got a really
strong support network.

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:10.240
What was your first I made it purchase.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:11.830
Oh my gosh, this is
gonna be so embarrassing.

00:05:11.830 --> 00:05:15.160
I was still living at my dad's house.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:18.250
My first purchase was a pre-owned Ferrari.

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:20.110
I went to the Ferrari
dealership and walked in.

00:05:20.110 --> 00:05:21.070
They looked, they must have looked at

00:05:21.070 --> 00:05:22.090
me like, what are you doing?

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:24.130
I was like, oh, can I buy a
car? And they were like, what?

00:05:24.130 --> 00:05:25.210
Yeah.
So I came the next day,

00:05:25.210 --> 00:05:26.920
gave 'em the cashier's
check and I drove home

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:29.290
and my dad was very upset

00:05:29.290 --> 00:05:30.370
because I, you know,

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:31.660
he's like, where are you
gonna park this thing?

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:32.800
I mean, not in front of my house.

00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:35.470
Instead of settling in the Bay Area,

00:05:35.470 --> 00:05:39.190
like most tech startups,
Snapchat's first official office

00:05:39.190 --> 00:05:41.710
that wasn't in Spiegel's
dad's house was in this

00:05:41.710 --> 00:05:43.660
small but iconic spot.

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:45.220
Welcome to the Blue house.

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:46.870
And just imagine there's a big ghost

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:48.310
right out front right there. So,

00:05:48.310 --> 00:05:51.130
So tourists would come by,
snap photos with the ghost and,

00:05:51.130 --> 00:05:53.080
And come up and, and knock
on the door to get help

00:05:53.080 --> 00:05:55.030
with their account too, and
give feedback, which is,

00:05:55.030 --> 00:05:56.680
is always appreciated.

00:05:56.680 --> 00:05:58.280
So why a ghost?

00:05:58.280 --> 00:05:59.870
Well, in the beginning
the app was called Peekaboo,

00:05:59.870 --> 00:06:01.430
so it was boo like a ghost.

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:04.310
And I drew the little
ghost in my dorm room.

00:06:04.310 --> 00:06:06.230
You drew it?
Yeah. Back in the day it was holding a

00:06:06.230 --> 00:06:07.760
Polaroid too, which is pretty cute.

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:10.100
But we simplified it,
got rid of the Polaroid

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:12.620
and now it's just the Snapchat ghost.

00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:15.205
You loved Venice, but
Venice didn't always love you.

00:06:15.205 --> 00:06:17.395
I mean, there was quite a bit of backlash.

00:06:17.395 --> 00:06:20.775
They go to the IPO, they go to the IPO,

00:06:20.775 --> 00:06:22.105
there are people holding signs.

00:06:22.105 --> 00:06:24.350
Venice is a community,
not a corporate campus.

00:06:24.350 --> 00:06:25.970
How did you handle that?

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:27.590
It's definitely a lively environment,

00:06:27.590 --> 00:06:30.500
but we, we never anticipated
that we would grow so quickly.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:32.210
And I think that did put some
pressure on the community

00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:34.040
and ultimately it's part
of the reason why we,

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:35.930
we ended up moving to our, our campus in,

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:37.310
in Santa Monica is the company sort

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:38.990
of reached a different phase of growth.

00:06:38.990 --> 00:06:41.630
But those early days will
always, you know, be a special,

00:06:41.630 --> 00:06:43.730
have a special place in my heart.

00:06:43.730 --> 00:06:45.230
As luck would have it, the current

00:06:45.230 --> 00:06:46.640
occupants of the Blue House

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:49.940
we're happy to let us in for
a tour to relive the memories.

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:52.070
Congrats on getting going. Thanks.

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:53.600
Yeah, hopefully we can have some

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:55.085
similar success to you guys.

00:06:55.085 --> 00:06:57.950
I, I have no doubt this
house is very lucky, I think.

00:06:57.950 --> 00:07:00.230
Hi, thanks for letting us crash your

00:07:00.230 --> 00:07:01.820
peaceful Venice morning.

00:07:01.820 --> 00:07:03.890
This is actually where
we all sat when we decided

00:07:03.890 --> 00:07:05.300
to stay in Los Angeles.

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:06.830
'cause that was a big debate at the time.

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:08.330
You know, our investors
were saying maybe move

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:09.680
to the Bay Area and this kind of thing.

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:12.440
We all sat here and kind of
heard everyone's perspective

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:13.640
and everyone wanted to stay.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:16.430
I shared a desk here with one
of our team members, Micah,

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:18.620
we were playing footsie under
the table sometimes.

00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:20.725
Oh my goodness. Look

00:07:20.725 --> 00:07:22.370
at that.

00:07:22.370 --> 00:07:23.665
I mean, that's a pretty magical spot. Not

00:07:23.665 --> 00:07:24.740
bad for a first office,

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:25.970
Not bad for a first office.

00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:30.590
Snap went public in 2017 and
left its startup days behind.

00:07:30.590 --> 00:07:32.990
But no matter how much
the company has changed,

00:07:32.990 --> 00:07:35.810
Spiegel has stayed
committed to his vision.

00:07:35.810 --> 00:07:37.970
It's easy to forget because
it's been so long now,

00:07:37.970 --> 00:07:40.130
but Snap popularized so many things

00:07:40.130 --> 00:07:43.910
that are just like a fact
of social media today.

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:45.950
Disappearing messages, stories, filters

00:07:45.950 --> 00:07:49.850
and lenses, even vertical
video location tags.

00:07:49.850 --> 00:07:54.350
What was it about you and Snap's
culture that enabled that?

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:56.510
Well, I, I think one of the
things that was really unique

00:07:56.510 --> 00:07:58.220
is that we were mobile first.

00:07:58.220 --> 00:07:59.930
So we were one of the first services

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:02.480
to start building mobile only A lot

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:04.880
of our competitors actually
had started on the desktop

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:06.290
and were migrating to mobile.

00:08:06.290 --> 00:08:08.420
But we had grown up with smartphones

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:10.130
and even things as simple as, you know,

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:12.050
back in the day when you would
open your camera, you had

00:08:12.050 --> 00:08:13.850
to choose between photo or video.

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:15.470
So we invented this
button where you would tap

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:18.350
to take a photo or press
and hold for video.

00:08:18.350 --> 00:08:20.690
It was the same of course for
stories for vertical video.

00:08:20.690 --> 00:08:22.220
It was so obvious to us.

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:25.310
I mean, all the video at the
time was cut horizontally.

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:27.650
So it was all about
making things more human.

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:30.890
Yeah. And, and easier to use,
designed around the, the way

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:32.780
that people live instead of forcing people

00:08:32.780 --> 00:08:35.720
to change the way they
live to use technology.

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:37.520
Snap has always made big waves

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:40.880
for its size in Silicon
Valley, inspiring copycats

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:43.340
and sparking some rivalries along the way.

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:46.640
Your LinkedIn says you're
the VP of product at Meta.

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:47.960
How do you really feel?

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:49.190
Well, I wish that was my joke

00:08:49.190 --> 00:08:52.460
'cause I get so much positive
feedback on on that one.

00:08:52.460 --> 00:08:53.810
You know, one of the fun parts

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:56.670
of being a designer is
building stuff that lots

00:08:56.670 --> 00:08:58.290
of people use, but it's also meant

00:08:58.290 --> 00:09:00.390
that from the very early days as we saw

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:02.460
how the competitive
landscape would play out,

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:04.200
that we invested in technology

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:06.180
that was highly differentiated.

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:08.280
That was very, very difficult to copy.

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:10.200
And that has platform characteristics.

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:12.030
This is legend, but I
wanna hear it from you.

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:15.750
Mark Zuckerberg famously
offered $3 billion

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:17.790
to buy you back in the day.

00:09:17.790 --> 00:09:20.850
Tell me about the
journey of emotions there

00:09:20.850 --> 00:09:24.720
and what gave you the courage to say no?

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:26.730
Well, I can say now
publicly, it was a hell

00:09:26.730 --> 00:09:29.130
of a lot more than that,
which is pretty wild.

00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:31.020
So I think for us there were

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:32.330
A, it was more than
three. You're saying six?

00:09:32.330 --> 00:09:34.955
A lot more than three
I Ish. Yeah, I think.

00:09:34.955 --> 00:09:39.510
Okay - I think for us,
there were a couple things.

00:09:39.510 --> 00:09:42.690
The first one was that we
saw a much bigger opportunity

00:09:42.690 --> 00:09:43.950
for, for Snapchat.

00:09:43.950 --> 00:09:45.930
A lot of that was informed by, you know,

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:48.000
having the experience
of watching Instagram,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.450
which sold very, very
early in their life as a,

00:09:51.450 --> 00:09:54.390
a company ultimately has
become a huge driver of growth

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:56.850
for Meta, an incredible business.

00:09:56.850 --> 00:09:58.620
And I think watching that

00:09:58.620 --> 00:10:00.780
and learning from that sort of story

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:02.370
and that feeling we had that wow, they,

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:04.320
they had sold way too early.

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:06.270
Definitely informed some of our thinking.

00:10:06.270 --> 00:10:08.850
But more importantly, we saw
